•	Config-driven: Entity definitions live in DynamoDB, not code. Add a new intent by inserting a row.
•	Anti-hallucination: Seven-layer validation ensures no fabricated values reach the caller. Values the caller did not literally say are rejected (wasExplicit check). Confidence threshold set to 0.95.
•	Flat response: Every value returned is a string. Connect only accepts flat key-value maps. No stringified JSON arrays.

•	Minimal response: Only entity values and control fields (status, count, missing_count, extraction_complete, intent) are returned.


{
  "{entity_name}": "{value}" or "NOT_FOUND",  // one per entity
  "count": "{found_count}",
  "missing_count": "{missing_count}",
  "extraction_complete": "true" or "false",
  "status": "COMPLETE" or "PARTIAL" or "EMPTY",
  "intent": "{enterpriseIntent}"
}



.1 End-to-End Flow
[Caller speaks]
      ↓
[Lambda 1: Intent Detection] → $.External.enterpriseIntent
      ↓
[Check: Does intent need entities?]
  ├─ No  → Handle directly (balance inquiry, transfer to agent)
  └─ Yes → [Lambda 2: Entity Extraction]
              ↓
          $.External.from_account = "savings"
          $.External.amount = "100"
          $.External.status = "COMPLETE"
              ↓
          [Check $.External.status]
            ├─ COMPLETE → Confirm → [Lambda 3: Fulfillment]
            ├─ PARTIAL  → Ask for missing → Loop back
            └─ EMPTY    → Ask caller to repeat → Loop back
2.2 Lambda 2 Internal Steps
Step 1.	Receive enterpriseIntent from Connect parameters (passed by Lambda 1 via Set contact attributes). Read CollectionConfig (DynamoDB) using ContactId to extract the last conversation segment’s transcript from UserInput fields.
Step 2.	Fetch entity definitions from IntentEntityDefinitions (DynamoDB) using enterpriseIntent as the partition key.
Step 3.	Build extraction prompt dynamically by looping through each entity definition. CONSTRAINED entities get allowedValues injected. OPEN entities get type rules.
Step 4.	Call Claude Opus 4.6 via Bedrock with temperature=0. Receive structured JSON with value, confidence, and wasExplicit per entity.
Step 5.	Validate every extraction: CONSTRAINED values checked against allowedValues list, OPEN values checked with type-specific rules, confidence below 0.85 rejected.
Step 6.	Flatten results into a flat string key-value map and return to Connect.
2.3 DynamoDB Tables
Table	Partition Key	Access Pattern	Purpose
IntentEntityDefinitions	enterpriseIntent (String)	GetItem by intent	What entities to extract per intent
CollectionConfig	ContactId (String)	GetItem by contact	Conversation turns + transcript
 
3. Data Stores
3.1 IntentEntityDefinitions Schema
Each item defines what entities to extract for a specific intent. The Lambda reads this table but never writes to it.
Partition Key: enterpriseIntent (String)
Billing Mode: PAY_PER_REQUEST (on-demand)
Region: us-west-2
3.1.1 Entity Definition Fields
Field	Type	Description	Example	Notes
entityName	String	Unique snake_case key	from_account	Becomes $.External key
entityType	Enum	CONSTRAINED or OPEN	CONSTRAINED	Drives validation path
entityDescription	String	Context for Claude	Account to transfer FROM	Disambiguates similar values
exampleUtterance	String	Natural phone speech	from my savings	Include filler words
allowedValues	List|null	Valid values (CONSTRAINED)	[checking, savings]	null for OPEN type
3.1.2 Entity Definition Best Practices
•	entityName: Use snake_case, be specific (transfer_date not date), match what Connect expects.
•	entityType: Use CONSTRAINED when a fixed list exists. Never use OPEN for something that has valid values.
•	entityDescription: Write as if explaining to a new employee. Include directional context ("account to transfer FROM").
•	exampleUtterance: Use casual phone speech with filler words ("from my savings" not "savings"). The surrounding words teach Claude the speech pattern.
•	allowedValues: All lowercase, simplest form. Include every valid value. Don’t include synonyms.
3.2 CollectionConfig Schema
Each item represents a complete conversation for a single call. The Lambda reads ConversationTurns to extract the transcript.
Partition Key: ContactId (String)
Key Fields: Typing, Indexing, CollectedSlots, ActionHistory, ConversationTurns
3.2.1 Conversation Segment Detection
The Lambda scans ConversationTurns and groups them into segments. A segment ends when a turn has a trigger of "transfer", "self_service", or "info" AND contains an enterpriseIntent field. Only the last segment is processed.
Turn 1: no-input-reprompt, UserInput=""               ← Skip
Turn 2: clarify, UserInput="transfer 100 from savings" ← Collect
Turn 3: transfer, enterpriseIntent="FUNDS_TRANSFER"    ← Segment 1
Turn 4: clarify, UserInput="block my card 4532"        ← Collect
Turn 5: self_service, enterpriseIntent="CARD_BLOCK"    ← Segment 2 (KEPT)
 
4. Lambda Response Format
Every response is a flat map of string key-value pairs. No nested objects, no arrays, no non-string values. The response contains only entity values and control fields.
4.1 Response Field Reference
Field	Values	Present	Purpose
{entity_name}	Extracted value or NOT_FOUND	When intent has entities	Flat key for Connect prompts and branching
count	0, 1, 2, 3...	Always	Number of successfully extracted entities
missing_count	0, 1, 2, 3...	Always	Number of entities still needed
extraction_complete	true | false	Always	All entities found?
status	COMPLETE | PARTIAL | EMPTY	Always	Primary flow branching field
intent	enterpriseIntent string	Always	Which intent was detected
That is the complete field set. No additional metadata, audit, confidence, disposition, or error detail fields are included in the response.
4.2 Status Values
•	COMPLETE: All entities defined for this intent were successfully extracted and validated. count equals the total entity count, missing_count is "0".
•	PARTIAL: Some entities were extracted but others are missing or failed validation. count is less than total, missing_count is greater than "0". Entity values that failed show "NOT_FOUND".
•	EMPTY: No entities could be extracted from the transcript. All entity values are "NOT_FOUND", count is "0", missing_count equals the total entity count.
4.3 Sample Responses
4.3.1 COMPLETE — All Entities Extracted
{
  "from_account": "savings",
  "to_account": "checking",
  "amount": "100",
  "transfer_date": "2026-04-11",
  "count": "4",
  "missing_count": "0",
  "extraction_complete": "true",
  "status": "COMPLETE",
