}
4.4 Why This Format
•	Minimal bytes: ~300-400 bytes for a 4-entity intent. No duplication, no wasted space.
•	Connect usability: Every field is directly accessible as $.External.{key}. No parsing needed.
•	Searchable: Flat keys are searchable in contact records and CloudWatch logs.
•	No stringified JSON: Arrays waste 3-5x the bytes, are unreadable in logs, and Connect cannot parse them.
•	Downstream Lambda compatibility: The fulfillment Lambda already knows which entities to expect from the intent. It reads flat keys directly, no array parsing needed.
 
5. Validation & Anti-Hallucination
The system uses six layers of defense to prevent hallucinated or incorrect values from reaching the caller. No single layer is relied upon alone.
Layer	Applies To	Mechanism	On Failure
1. Prompt rules	All entities	Strict instructions in system prompt	Claude returns null
2. AllowedValues	CONSTRAINED only	Hard if-in-list check in code	Entity marked NOT_FOUND
3. Type validation	OPEN only	Regex + type checks (amount, date, digits)	Entity marked NOT_FOUND
4. Confidence	All entities	Reject below 0.85 threshold	Entity marked NOT_FOUND
5. wasExplicit	All entities	Flag if interpreted vs stated	Informs confidence check
6. temperature=0	All entities	Deterministic LLM output	Same input = same output
5.1 CONSTRAINED Validation
For entities with a fixed set of valid values, the validator performs a hard membership check. If Claude returns "bank_account" but allowedValues is ["checking", "savings", "money_market"], the value is immediately rejected. This is the primary anti-hallucination defense for enumerated fields.
5.2 OPEN Validation
For free-form entities, the validator applies type-specific checks based on the entity name:
•	amount, wire_amount, loan_payment_amount, dispute_amount: Valid positive number under 10 million.
•	transfer_date, payment_date, transaction_date, travel dates, start_date: ISO YYYY-MM-DD format.
•	routing_number: Exactly 9 digits.
•	card_last_four: Exactly 4 digits.
•	account_number, external_account_number: 4-17 digits.
•	percentage: 0-100.
5.3 What Happens on Validation Failure
When any entity fails validation, its value in the response is set to "NOT_FOUND". The count decreases, missing_count increases, and status becomes PARTIAL (or EMPTY if nothing passes). Connect then checks $.External.status and prompts the caller for the missing values.
 
6. Contact Attribute Budget (32 KB)
AWS Connect enforces a hard limit of 32,768 UTF-8 bytes across all contact attributes. When exceeded in a Set contact attributes block, the contact routes to the Error branch.
6.1 Byte Estimation
Category	Fields	Est. Bytes	Notes
Control fields	status, extraction_complete, count, missing_count, intent	~130 bytes	Fixed size
Entity values (4 entities)	from_account, to_account, amount, transfer_date	~80 bytes	Scales with entity count
Lambda 1 attributes	enterpriseIntent, trigger	~80 bytes	Already on contact
System attributes	Channel, Queue, Agent, etc.	~1-2 KB	Connect managed
TOTAL (4 entity intent)	All above	~300-400 bytes	Well under 32 KB
TOTAL (15 entity intent)	All above scaled	~800-1000 bytes	Still safe
6.2 Budget Management Best Practices
•	Use flow attributes for temporary data that doesn’t need to persist across flows.
•	Clean up attributes by setting value to empty string ("") once no longer needed.
•	Never use stringified JSON arrays. They duplicate data and waste 3-5x the bytes.
•	Keep attribute keys short: from_account (12 bytes) not customer_source_account_name (30 bytes).
•	Save Lambda 2 values to $.Attributes before invoking Lambda 3, since $.External is overwritten.
•	Audit total attribute size periodically when adding new intents with many entities.
 
7. Connect Flow Integration
7.1 Flow Branching Pattern
[Check $.External.status]
  ├─ "COMPLETE" → Confirm with caller → Fulfill
  ├─ "PARTIAL"  → Check $.External.{entity} == "NOT_FOUND"
  │     → Prompt for each NOT_FOUND entity
  │     → Loop back to Lambda 2
  └─ "EMPTY"    → "Could you repeat that?"
        → Loop back to Lambda 2
7.2 Using Entity Values in Prompts
Play prompt blocks directly reference flat keys:
"I'll transfer $.External.amount dollars from your
 $.External.from_account to your $.External.to_account.
 Is that correct?"
Caller hears: "I’ll transfer 100 dollars from your savings to your checking. Is that correct?"
7.3 Handling NOT_FOUND in PARTIAL
When status is PARTIAL, check each entity value for NOT_FOUND to determine which prompts to play:
[Check $.External.from_account]
  ├─ "NOT_FOUND" → Play: "Which account to transfer from?"
  └─ Any other   → Skip (already have it)

[Check $.External.amount]
  ├─ "NOT_FOUND" → Play: "How much to transfer?"
  └─ Any other   → Skip
7.4 Attribute Persistence Across Lambdas
$.External is completely replaced when a new Lambda is invoked. Save Lambda 2 values to $.Attributes before calling Lambda 3:
[Lambda 2 returns] → $.External.from_account = "savings"
      ↓
[Set contact attributes]
  Key: from_account   Value: $.External.from_account
  Key: amount         Value: $.External.amount
      ↓
[Lambda 3: Fulfillment] → $.External is overwritten
      ↓
$.Attributes.from_account = "savings"       ← Preserved
$.External.confirmation_number = "TXN-001"  ← From Lambda 3
 

















